Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been severely hit by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because after the crisis, the global economy is unbalanced in many aspects, particularly in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the cause of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
First of all, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when the bubbles burst, when the markets freeze, and when no credit is available anymore) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without warning signs.
Periodic outbreaks of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could lead to excessive regulation, a reassertion of state control, and a retreat from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a crisis of sovereign debt for advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can lead to a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration in tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Unbalances and undetected systemic risks mean that fiscal policies that seem prudent are not actually prudent.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But his income and expenses were largely determined by a real estate bubble linked to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which tax consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is certainly a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of assets through restructurings or through inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this type of sequential imbalance in cascades, then "sovereign" states must be alert to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking corrective measures quickly.
New detailed legislative frameworks emphasizing capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings and other information sources, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms are about to be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will not at all resolve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and heralding instability.
In addition to and complementary to new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some prominent politicians and analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, constantly evolving global financial system mean, according to them, that risk detection is either impossible or so prone to error that such an effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we then have to accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that we cannot predict in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under conditions of uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists in rejecting a true proposition, and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let us denote RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
This question can be phrased as follows: within the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest cost?
The opponents of prudent supervision of systemic risks hold two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable indicator of an increasing potential instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
It must be admitted, however, that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable, and they certainly did not foresee the tipping point.
They were, however, undeniably signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but that they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a likely higher cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the disease.
No doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (FAP) must be significant to be convincing.
I, for my part, am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend toward opening up.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty, and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be the opposite: that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refrain from acting unless one has good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at best questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we could eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop, and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try this experiment, and for that purpose assign responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, that possesses sharp analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and that is relatively free from conflicts of interest.
Her analysis should be made public and could therefore influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the financial system's ability to regulate itself.
